'The sea is ours': Bolivia's landlocked country hopes the vessel will open the way to the Pacific again
The Marines are constantly patrolling the rigged outpost at La Paz.
The ocean blue flag is waved over public buildings.
The naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are decorated with the motto: "The sea is ours by right.
It's our duty to get him back.
Throughout Bolivia, which has no access to the ocean, the memory of the lost outlet handed to Chile after a bloody conflict in the 19th century is still alive  as is the call to sail the Pacific again.
In fact, that hope is now stronger than it has been in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the international court on October 1 after five years of deliberation.
"The strength is in Bolivia, there is a feeling of cheerfulness and unity everywhere, and the country expects a positive result", said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzada.
Many Bolivians will be watching the International Court of Justice ruling on the big screen across the country, hoping that the Hague tribunal will uphold Bolivia's claim and that after decades of negotiations, Chile will be obliged to give Bolivia sovereign access to the ocean.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, who is set to face a contentious reelection battle next year, also staked heavily on the court's judgement on Monday.
"We are very close to regaining access to the Pacific Ocean", promised Morales last August.
But some analysts believe that the likelihood of the court's ruling in favor of Bolivia is very low, and even if it did, it would not change the reality of the situation.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no authority to take Chilean territory and has decided not to determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the international court's ruling is only six months after hearing the last arguments indicates that the case is 'not complicated', replies Paz Zarate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And instead of helping the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may actually have hurt it.
"The problem of access to the ocean has been exacerbated by the current government of Bolivia", Zarate said.
Then he suggested that Morales' belligerent rhetoric had erased what little goodwill Chile had left.
Bolivia and Chile will at some point continue negotiations, but it will be extremely difficult to have a normal dialogue after what happened.
The two countries have not maintained diplomatic missions to each other since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Velze, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, dismissed the idea that the court's decision was being made unusually quickly.
He said that on Monday, Bolivia will have "an incredible opportunity to open the page of a new era in its relations with Chile, and a chance to end 139 years of disagreement by achieving mutual benefits".
Calzada also rejected the idea that Morales - who continues to be one of the most popular presidents in Latin America - has used the issue of access to the ocean as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific Ocean", he added.
"Reflection is an opportunity to see that we have to overcome our past problems".
