John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a reputation for academic excellence, which continues in 2018 with another outstanding performance in examination results, only reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, the arts, music and other social sciences.
With up to 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Association of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the best possible level to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further education, their career choices and their place in a global world.
As an education sector that can design and implement a personalised curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said this: "If you talk to someone in a language they understand, what you say will reach them.
But if you speak to him in his own language, you touch his heart.
It's a powerful reminder that we can't rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and trust with the people of other countries.
And from this year's test results, we see that languages are at the top of the list with the highest achievement for independent schools.
A total of 68% of pupils who had studied a foreign language achieved a high grade of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of pupils achieved A in Chinese, 72% in German, 69% in French and 63% in Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland see foreign languages as a vital skill that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
At present, languages as a subject of free choice by pupils receive the same treatment as natural-mathematical disciplines (scientific, technological, engineering and mathematical disciplines) both in and outside the curricula of independent schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills showed that 17% of employers cited insufficient language skills as a reason for finding employees.
Therefore, increasingly, foreign language skills are becoming mandatory to prepare young people for their future careers.
More and more jobs require the knowledge of a foreign language, making these skills essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career path chosen, if one masters a foreign language, one will have a real advantage in the future, having mastered such a skill, which remains for a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts the multilingual person one step ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to conduct a language test, with French being the only language to reach double-digit proficiency at 15%.
And that's why investing in language learning today is important for kids now.
Speaking several languages, especially in developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding good jobs.
In Scotland, each school will be different in the languages taught.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered to be more important for the UK in the future to 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be enough languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are experts in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are committed to providing an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed in life, no matter what the future holds.
It cannot be denied that in a global business environment, languages continue to play an incredibly important role in the future of any country, which requires that this be taken into account in the education system.
And indeed, modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, along with diversity and excellence, to young people in Scotland.
I must do it well.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Association.
