North Korea says there's no way to disarm unilaterally without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that the continued sanctions deepened mistrust of the United States and there was no way the country could give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
At the annual general assembly of the world body, Ri Yong-ho said that "significant goodwill measures" have been taken in the past year, such as a halt to nuclear and missile tests, the destruction of the nuclear test site, and pledges to not proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
"We are not seeing a response from the US, however", he said.
Without trust in the United States, we will not have faith in our own national security and there is no way under any circumstances that we will be the first to disarm unilaterally.
While Ri expressed North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking step-by-step steps, his statement seemed significant as he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work for the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula, and Trump gave assurances on North Korea's security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the U.S. says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The US is insisting that we first eliminate nuclear weapons" and increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal through coercion, and even objecting to the "declaration of ending the war", Ri said.
The notion that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a meaningless dream of those who do not know us.
The problem is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust".
Ri did not mention whether a second meeting between Kim and Trump was planned, which the US leader highlighted through the UN earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister focused on the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months and added: "If the nuclear disarmament side was South Korea, not the US, the Korean Peninsula's nuclear disarmament would not have come to such a standstill.
However, the tone of Ri's speech was significantly different from the previous year, when he told the UN General Assembly that the targeting of North Korean missiles on the US mainland was inevitable, after the late President Trump called Kim "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
At the UN this year, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea with "total destruction", praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still much work to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea denuclearises.
On Wednesday, Trump stressed that there is no deadline for this, saying, "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months".
China and Russia are arguing that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that: "Enforcement of Security Council sanctions must necessarily continue until complete, final and verified nuclear disarmament is achieved".
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to stop funding Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip didn't go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying he had made progress, but only hours later North Korea accused him of making "gangster demands".
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea promised to destroy a missile site and a nuclear complex if the U.S. took "appropriate action".
He said Kim told him that the "appropriate measures" he was seeking were the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and that he wanted to achieve normalization with Washington.
Harvard students on a course on getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is making all students sleep more in an attempt to combat the growing culture of all-night caffeinated learning.
A professor has found that students at the world's number one university often do not even consider the very basics of how to care for themselves.
Charles Keisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed what he believes is the first course of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after speaking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
And then this girl came up to me and said, "Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?"
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being offered for the first time this year, is teaching students the most important things about how good sleep habits help with academic and athletic performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barrera, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there's a picture of a dorm room where students are clicking on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of bedtime routines.
Another part of the study tells participants how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Then a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
We know that this won't immediately change the behavior of the students.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the health effects of your choice to smoke", added Prof. Keisler.
The culture of pride in studying all night still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students means that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Getting enough and quality sleep should be the students' "secret weapon" in fighting stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he says, even to avoid obesity, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into a starvation mode that makes them hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Keisler design the course by taking one of his classes during his first year at Harvard.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to spread it around the campus.
It is hoped that the next step is to require all graduate students to complete a similar degree programme before joining a competing institution.
Professor Kessler recommends that students consider setting a bedtime and wake-up alarm and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause trouble falling asleep.
