Yearbook: The inventor of the Geiger counter
A page from our Sunday Morning yearbook: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago and a day... the day the future physicist Johann Wilhelm Hans Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the creation of the device known as the Geiger counter.
A cornerstone of science ever since, the Geiger counter became a cornerstone of pop culture when in 1950 the movie "The Bells of Coronado" was released, starring the seemingly incredible scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans.
What, for God's sake, is this?
It's a geiger counter and it's used to detect radioactive minerals, like uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms being released by the radioactivity in the minerals.
It's definitely raining right now!
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just a few days after his 63rd birthday.
But the discovery that bears his name lives on.
A new cancer vaccine could train the immune system to recognize foreign cells
A new cancer vaccine can train the immune system to recognize foreign cells and kill them
The vaccine trains the immune system to recognize foreign cells as part of the treatment
The method involves taking immune cells from the patient and modifying them in a laboratory
They can then look for a protein that is common to many types of cancer and inject it back into the patient
The trial vaccine has shown promising results in patients with various cancers.
A woman treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize foreign cells saw her ovarian cancer go away for more than 18 months.
The method involves taking immune cells from the patient and modifying them in a laboratory so that they can make a protein common to many cancers called HER2, and then injecting them back into the patient.
According to Professor Jay Berzofsky of the US National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland: "Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine".
HER2 stimulates the growth of several cancers, including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancer, explained Prof. Berzofsky.
A similar approach of taking immune cells from patients and 'training' them to target cancer cells has been used in the treatment of a type of leukaemia.
