Since 2011, Global Citizen has recorded more than 19 million actions by its supporters, advocating for a multitude of different causes.
It says that these actions have helped world leaders announce commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, which will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and communications arising from its actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been paid or collected.
The group estimates that the funds have already directly impacted nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key commitments include the 'Power of Nutrition' UK-based investor-developer partnership, the 'Helping Children to Reach Their Full Potential' commitment, which promises to provide Rwanda with $35 million to help end malnutrition in the country, after receiving more than 4700 tweets from 'global citizens'.
"With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and global citizens like you, we can make the social injustice of malnutrition just a historical note", Power of Food Ambassador Tracy Ulman told an audience at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5,000 actions were taken calling on the UK to improve maternal and child nutrition, the government has announced funding for a project, 'The Power of Nutrition', which will reach 5 million women and children.
In response to one of the WFP's on its website, asking "Why do you think we can end extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen replied: It will be a long and difficult journey. We will fail sometimes and we will fail again.
But just like the great civil rights and anti-apartheid movements before us, we will succeed because we are stronger together.
