One of his grandsons, Michael Van, said it was "extremely symbolic" that the monument was unveiled exactly 100 years after his grandfather's work was awarded the medal.
According to the London Gazette of 29 September 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Van led his battalion across the Canal de Saint-Quentin "in very thick fog and under heavy artillery and machine gun fire".
Later he attacked the line of fire and with "incredible courage" led the line forward before he attacked an artillery cannon with one hand and killed three of the squad.
Lieutenant Colonel Van was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Van, 72, said his grandfather's actions were "something I know I could never do, but it makes me humble".
He and his brother Dr. James Wang placed a wreath after the parade, led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
