Germany is delaying the launch of a new warship again.
The German Navy's newest frigate was supposed to be commissioned in 2014 to replace aging Cold War-era warships, but that won't happen until at least next year because of broken systems and skyrocketing costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the flagship of the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quotes an army spokesman.
The vessel was due to join the navy in 2014, but problems that arose after its delivery affected the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships ordered by the fleet in 2007 will replace the ageing Bremen-class frigates.
Understandably, they will have a powerful weaponry, a suite of air and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods. The newest frigates must be able to be used for up to two years before returning to their home ports.
But the continuing delays mean that the cutting-edge warships - which are said to allow Germany to show strength overseas - will be old when they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The ill-fated F125 made headlines last year when the German Navy formally refused to put the vessel into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the Navy has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after a delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media have cited a number of significant "software and hardware defects" that make the warship unusable if sent on a combat mission.
The software shortcomings are particularly important as the Baden-Wuerttemberg class vessels will be manned by a crew of around 120 seamen  only half the crew of the older Bremen class frigates.
In addition, the ship was found to be significantly overloaded, which reduced its efficiency and limited the Navy's ability to add future upgrades.
The 7,000-tonne Rheinland-Pfalz is thought to be twice the weight of ships of a similar class used by the Germans during World War II.
Aside from the defective hardware, the cost of the entire project - including training for the crew - also becomes a problem.
It is estimated to have reached a staggering €3.1 billion ($3.6 billion) from the original €2.2 billion.
The problems with the newest frigates are becoming particularly important in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval forces are shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defense committee, admitted that the navy was actually "running out of ships capable of carrying out missions".
The official said the problem has grown over time, as the old ships have been decommissioned but no new ones have been delivered.
He complained that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates could be brought into the fleet.
The National Trust is tracking the secret lives of bats
A new study conducted at a mansion in the Scottish Highlands aims to find out how bats use the landscape when they hunt.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation efforts.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow the common bats as well as the brown arrowheads water nightshades at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key points on the estate to track the activities of the bats during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also be conducting mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all the recordings will determine the frequencies of the bats' calls, as well as which species are making them.
A habitat map and report will then be drawn to create a detailed landscape picture of their behaviour.
Rob Duar, conservation adviser for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to the bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. the creation of meadows, and the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and Britain in general have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction activities that affect their shelters and lead to habitat loss.
Population risks may be posed by wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical treatments of building materials, and attacks by domestic cats.
Actually, bats are not blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation techniques to detect insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of national importance and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The Trust has trained experts who conduct regular surveys, inspections of the shelters and, on occasion, rescue operations.
The organisation has even set up Scotland's first and only special bat reserve at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten bat species in Scotland.
The manor's manager, David Thompson, says it's the perfect location for them.
"Here in Threave, we have a great terrain for bats", he noted.
We have old buildings, very old trees and a finished habitat.
But there's still a lot about bats that isn't known, so the work we're doing here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.
He emphasises the importance of checking for bats before undertaking property maintenance activities, as it is possible for the inadvertent destruction of a single sanctuary to kill up to 400 females and young bats, as well as to wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their habitats.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer with the Bat Trust, urged the public to help.
She said, "I still have a lot to learn about our bats and about many of our animal species, because we just don't know what's happening with their populations".
