Earthquakes and Tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people were killed by a powerful earthquake and tsunami that struck the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, authorities said, with the death toll expected to rise.
Due to the disrupted communications, aid organizations are unable to receive information from the Donggala Regency, an area north of Palu that is closer to the epicenter of the 7.5 magnitude earthquake.
More than 16,000 people were evacuated from Palu after the disaster.
Here are some key facts about Palu and Dongola, which are found on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi province, located at the end of a narrow beach strip on the west coast of the island of Sulawesi, with a population of 379,800 as of 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when it was hit by the earthquake and tsunami.
Dongala is a regency that stretches for more than 300 km (180 miles) along the coastline of Sulawesi Island.
The Regency, which is an administrative region smaller than a province, has an estimated population of 299,200 in 2017.
Fishing and farming are the mainstays of the economy of central Sulawesi province, especially in the coastal area of Dongola.
Nickel mining is also important to the province, but is concentrated mainly in Morlilla, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times in the past 100 years, according to the Indonesian Disaster Recovery Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of buildings in Dongola.
A tsunami hit the western part of Dongola in 1996 and killed nine people.
Indonesia is located on the seismic "Pacific Ring of Fire" and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunami waves in recent years:
2004: A powerful earthquake on December 26 off the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in North Sumatra triggered a tsunami that hit 14 countries and killed 226,000 people across the Indian Ocean coastline, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the western coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on Nias Island off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake hits Indonesia's most populous island, Java, triggering a tsunami that slams into the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake struck near the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake rocks one of the Mentawai Islands and activates a 10-meter wave tsunami that destroys dozens of villages and kills about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake hit the Pidi Jaya Regency in Aceh, causing destruction and panic as people remembered the devastation from the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time, no tsunami was triggered, but more than 100 people were killed by collapsed buildings.
2018: Strong earthquakes hit the tourist island of Lombok in Indonesia, killing more than 500 people, most of them on the northern side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and left thousands of tourists temporarily stranded.
