News for the red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manti and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
The Committee has reported decreasing growth conditions in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties  this shows decreasing concentrations.
The red tide floodplain stretches for approximately 130 miles along the coast from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
Algae patches can be seen up to 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but they're less than last week.
Red tide is also being observed in Pasco County.
Over the past week, there are reports of moderate concentrations in the coastal zone or slightly inland in Pinellas County, low to high concentrations in the coastal zone of Hillsborough County, high concentrations in the coastal zone of Manatee County, high concentrations in the coastal zone or inland in Sarasota County, moderate concentrations in Charlotte County, high concentrations in the coastal zone or inland in Lehigh County, and low concentrations in Cooley County.
Respiratory tract infections are continuing to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of respiratory infections in Northwest Florida in the past week.
